                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords">
                            About 12 years ago, I learned to play Majhong. I've been hooked ever since. But I've long wondered: Why don't more Americans play this great game? It's not so different from a game like Rummy, and you get to use cool tiles instead of boring old playing cards. There is one big difference between Mahjong and most American card games, though: It's really, really hard to score. Playing is easy, but scoring a hand can be very complicated, with lots of little caveats that change depending on where you're playing and who you're playing with.
                            <LineBreak />
                            <LineBreak />
                            In addition to complicated scoring, Mahjong games tend to go on for a long time. One game goes on for many rounds. At family gatherings, we bring out a notebook with games dating back years, and try to find a match with whichever four people we happen to have together at that time.
                            <LineBreak />
                            <LineBreak />
                            I built this app to do two things: 1.) Calculate scores quickly and easily, and 2.) Keep track of ongoing games. 
                            <LineBreak />
                            <LineBreak />
                            One thing I should note: The scoring system used in this app is based on the standard Japanese rules for Mahjong. Even though the game originated in China, it is very popular in Japan. Those are the rules I learned on, but I hope to update this app in the future to support additional rule sets.
                            <LineBreak />
                            <LineBreak />
                            I really built this app for myself and my family, but I hope that you will find it useful as well. Enjoy!
                        </TextBlock>

